# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: secure-boot-measured
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This may be done by hardware or firmware in the CPU, or by a separate processor in the computer system.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] On some systems, a power-on reset (POR) does not initiate booting, and the operator must initiate booting after POR completes.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] IBM uses the term **Initial Program Load** (**IPL**) on some product lines.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Restarting a computer is also called *rebooting*, which can be "hard", e.g., after electrical power to the CPU is switched from off to on, or "soft", where the power is not cut.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] On some systems, a soft boot may optionally clear RAM to zero.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Both hard and soft booting can be initiated by hardware, such as a button press, or by a software command.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Booting is complete when the operative runtime system, typically the operating system and some applications, is attained.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The process of returning a computer from a state of sleep (suspension) does not involve booting; however, restoring it from a state of hibernation does.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Minimally, some embedded systems do not require a noticeable boot sequence to begin functioning, and when turned on, may simply run operational programs that are stored in read-only memory (ROM).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] All computing systems are state machines, and a reboot may be the only method to return to a designated zero-state from an unintended, locked state.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] In addition to loading an operating system or stand-alone utility, the boot process can also load a storage dump program for diagnosing problems in an operating system.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The earliest known recorded use of "boot" as the shortened form for "bootstrap" is 1975.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] There are many different methods available to load a short initial program into a computer.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] These methods range from simple, physical input to removable media that can hold more complex programs.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Early computers in the 1940s and 1950s were one-of-a-kind engineering efforts that could take weeks to program, and program loading was one of many problems that had to be solved.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] An early computer, ENIAC, had no program stored in memory but was set up for each problem by a configuration of interconnecting cables.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Bootstrapping did not apply to ENIAC, whose hardware configuration was ready for solving problems as soon as power was applied.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The EDSAC system, the second stored-program computer to be built, used stepping switches to transfer a fixed program into memory when its start button was pressed.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The program stored on this device, which David Wheeler completed in late 1948, loaded further instructions from punched tape and then executed them.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The first programmable computers for commercial sale, such as the UNIVAC I and the IBM 701 included features to make their operation simpler.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] They typically included instructions that performed a complete input or output operation.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The same hardware logic could be used to load the contents of a punch card (the most typical ones) or other input media, such as a magnetic drum or magnetic tape, that contained a bootstrap program by pressing a single button.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This booting concept was called a variety of names for IBM computers of the 1950s and early 1960s, but IBM used the term "Initial Program Load" with the IBM 7030 Stretch and later used it for their mainframe lines, starting with the System/360 in 1964.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The IBM 701 computer (1952–1956) had a "Load" button that initiated reading of the first 36-bit word into main memory from a punched card in a card reader, a magnetic tape in a tape drive, or a magnetic drum unit, depending on the position of the Load Selector switch.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The left 18-bit half-word was then executed as an instruction, which usually read additional words into memory.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The loaded boot program was then executed, which, in turn, loaded a larger program from that medium into memory without further help from the human operator.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The IBM 704, IBM 7090, and IBM 7094 had similar mechanisms, but with different load buttons for different devices.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The term "boot" has been used in this sense since at least 1958.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Other IBM computers of that era had similar features.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] For example, the IBM 1401 system (1959) used a card reader to load a program from a punched card.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The 80 characters stored in the punched card were read into memory locations 001 to 080, then the computer would branch to memory location 001 to read its first stored instruction.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This instruction was always the same: move the information in these first 80 memory locations to an assembly area where the information in punched cards 2, 3, 4, and so on, could be combined to form the stored program.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Once this information was moved to the assembly area, the machine would branch to an instruction in location 080 (read a card) and the next card would be read and its information processed.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Another example was the IBM 650 (1953), a decimal machine, which had a group of ten 10-position switches on its operator panel that were addressable as a memory word (address 8000) and could be executed as an instruction.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Thus, setting the switches to 7004000400 and pressing the appropriate button would read the first card in the card reader into memory (op code 70), starting at address 400 and then jump to 400 to begin executing the program on that card.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] IBM's competitors also offered single-button program load.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] A noteworthy variation of this is found on the Burroughs B1700, where there is neither a boot ROM nor a hardwired IPL operation.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Instead, after the system is reset, it reads and executes microinstructions sequentially from a cassette tape drive mounted on the front panel; this sets up a boot loader in RAM, which is then executed.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] However, since this makes few assumptions about the system it can equally well be used to load diagnostic (Maintenance Test Routine) tapes which display an intelligible code on the front panel even in cases of gross CPU failure.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] In the IBM System/360 and its successors, including the current z/Architecture machines, the boot process is known as *Initial Program Load* (IPL).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] IBM coined this term for the 7030 (Stretch), revived it for the design of the System/360, and continues to use it in those environments today.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] In the System/360 processors, an IPL is initiated by the computer operator by selecting the three hexadecimal digit device address (CUU; C=I/O Channel address, UU=Control unit and Device address) followed by pressing the *LOAD* button.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] On the high end System/360 models, most System/370 and some later systems, the functions of the switches and the LOAD button are simulated using selectable areas on the screen of a graphics console, often an IBM 2250-like device or an IBM 3270-like device.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] For example, on the System/370 Model 158, the keyboard sequence 0-7-X (zero, seven and X, in that order) results in an IPL from the device address that was keyed into the input area.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The Amdahl 470V/6 and related CPUs supported four hexadecimal digits on those CPUs that had the optional second channel unit installed, for a total of 32 channels.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Later, IBM would also support more than 16 channels.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The IPL function in the System/360 and its successors prior to IBM Z, and its compatibles, such as Amdahl's, reads 24 bytes from an operator-specified device into main storage starting at real address zero.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The second and third groups of eight bytes are treated as Channel Command Words (CCWs) to continue loading the startup program (the first CCW is always simulated by the CPU and consists of a Read IPL command, 02h, with command chaining and suppress incorrect length indication being enforced).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] When the I/O channel commands are complete, the first group of eight bytes is then loaded into the processor's Program Status Word (PSW) and the startup program begins execution at the location designated by that PSW.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] IBM introduced some evolutionary changes in the IPL process, changing some details for System/370 Extended Architecture (S/370-XA) and later, and adding a new type of IPL for z/Architecture.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Minicomputers, starting with the Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-5 and PDP-8 (1965) simplified design by using the CPU to assist input and output operations.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This saved cost but made booting more complicated than pressing a single button.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Minicomputers typically had some way to *toggle in* short programs by manipulating an array of switches on the front panel.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Since the early minicomputers used magnetic-core memory, which did not lose its information when power was off, these bootstrap loaders would remain in place unless they were erased.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Erasure sometimes happened accidentally when a program bug caused a loop that overwrote all of memory.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Other minicomputers with such simple form of booting include Hewlett-Packard's HP 2100 series (mid-1960s), the original Data General Nova (1969), and DEC's PDP-4 (1962) and PDP-11 (1970).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] As the I/O operations needed to cause a read operation on a minicomputer I/O device were typically different for different device controllers, different bootstrap programs were needed for different devices.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] DEC later added, in 1971, an optional diode matrix read-only memory for the PDP-11 that stored a bootstrap program of up to 32 words (64 bytes).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] It consisted of a printed circuit card, the M792, that plugged into the Unibus and held a 32 by 16 array of semiconductor diodes.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] With all 512 diodes in place, the memory contained all "one" bits; the card was programmed by cutting off each diode whose bit was to be "zero".
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] DEC also sold versions of the card, the BM792-Yx series, pre-programmed for many standard input devices by simply omitting the unneeded diodes.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Following the older approach, the earlier PDP-1 has a hardware loader, such that an operator needs only push the *load* switch to instruct the paper tape reader to load a program directly into core memory.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The PDP-7, PDP-9, and PDP-15 successors to the PDP-4 have an added Read-In button to read a program in from paper tape and jump to it.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The Data General Supernova used front panel switches to cause the computer to automatically load instructions into memory from a device specified by the front panel's data switches, and then jump to loaded code.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] In a minicomputer with a paper tape reader, the first program to run in the boot process, the boot loader, would read into core memory either the second-stage boot loader (often called a *Binary Loader*) that could read paper tape with checksum or the operating system from an outside storage medium.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] A related example is based on a loader for a Nicolet Instrument Corporation minicomputer of the 1970s, using the paper tape reader-punch unit on a Teletype Model 33 ASR teleprinter.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The bytes of its second-stage loader are read from paper tape in reverse order.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The length of the second stage loader is such that the final byte overwrites location 7.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] After the instruction in location 6 executes, location 7 starts the second stage loader executing.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The second stage loader then waits for the much longer tape containing the operating system to be placed in the tape reader.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The difference between the boot loader and second stage loader is the addition of checking code to trap paper tape read errors, a frequent occurrence with relatively low-cost, "part-time-duty" hardware, such as the Teletype Model 33 ASR.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The earliest microcomputers, such as the Altair 8800 (released first in 1975) and an even earlier, similar machine (based on the Intel 8008 CPU) had no bootstrapping hardware as such.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] When powered up, the CPU would see memory that would contain random data.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The front panels of these machines carried toggle switches for entering addresses and data, one switch per bit of the computer memory word and address bus.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Simple additions to the hardware permitted one memory location at a time to be loaded from those switches to store bootstrap code.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Meanwhile, the CPU was kept from attempting to execute memory content.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Once correctly loaded, the CPU was enabled to execute the bootstrapping code.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This process, similar to that used for several earlier minicomputers, was tedious and had to be error-free.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The introduction of integrated circuit read-only memory (ROM), with its many variants, including mask-programmed ROMs, programmable ROMs (PROM), erasable programmable ROMs (EPROM), and flash memory, reduced the physical size and cost of ROM.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This allowed firmware boot programs to be included as part of the computer.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The Data General Nova 1200 (1970) and Nova 800 (1971) had a program load switch that, in combination with options that provided two ROM chips, loaded a program into main memory from those ROM chips and jumped to it.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Digital Equipment Corporation introduced the integrated-circuit-ROM-based BM873 (1974), M9301 (1977), M9312 (1978), REV11-A and REV11-C, MRV11-C, and MRV11-D ROM memories, all usable as bootstrap ROMs.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] An Italian telephone switching computer, called "Gruppi Speciali", patented in 1975 by Alberto Ciaramella, a researcher at CSELT, included an (external) ROM.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Gruppi Speciali was, starting from 1975, a fully single-button machine booting into the operating system from a ROM memory composed of semiconductors, not ferrite cores.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Although the ROM device was not natively embedded in the computer of Gruppi Speciali, due to the design of the machine, it also allowed the single-button ROM booting in machines not designed for that (therefore, this "bootstrap device" was architecture-independent), e.g., the PDP-11.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Storing the state of the machine after the switch-off was also in place, which was another critical feature in the telephone switching contest.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Some minicomputers and superminicomputers include a separate console processor that bootstraps the main processor.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The PDP-11/44 had an Intel 8085 as a console processor; the VAX-11/780, the first member of Digital's VAX line of 32-bit superminicomputers, had an LSI-11-based console processor, and the VAX-11/730 had an 8085-based console processor.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] These console processors could boot the main processor from various storage devices.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Some other superminicomputers, such as the VAX-11/750, implement console functions, including the first stage of booting, in CPU microcode.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] A system built using that microprocessor will have the permanent ROM occupying these special locations so that the system always begins operating without operator assistance.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] For example, Intel x86 processors always start by running the instructions beginning at F000:FFF0, while for the MOS 6502 processor, initialization begins by reading a two-byte vector address at $FFFD (MS byte) and $FFFC (LS byte) and jumping to that location to run the bootstrap code.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Apple Computer's first computer, the Apple 1, introduced in 1976, featured PROM chips that eliminated the need for a front panel for the boot process (as was the case with the Altair 8800) in a commercial computer.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Due to the expense of read-only memory at the time, the Apple II booted its disk operating systems using a series of very small incremental steps, each passing control onward to the next phase of the gradually more complex boot process.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Because so little of the disk operating system relied on ROM, the hardware was also extremely flexible and supported a wide range of customized disk copy protection mechanisms.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Some operating systems, most notably pre-1995 Macintosh systems from Apple, are so closely interwoven with their hardware that it is impossible to natively boot an operating system other than the standard one.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This is the opposite extreme of the scenario using switches mentioned above; it is highly inflexible but relatively error-proof and foolproof as long as all hardware is working normally.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] A common solution in such situations is to design a boot loader that works as a program belonging to the standard OS that hijacks the system and loads the alternative OS.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This technique was used by Apple for its A/UX Unix implementation and copied by various freeware operating systems and BeOS Personal Edition 5.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Some machines, like the Atari ST microcomputer, were "instant-on", with the operating system executing from a ROM.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Retrieval of the OS from secondary or tertiary store was thus eliminated as one of the characteristic operations for bootstrapping.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] To allow system customizations, accessories, and other support software to be loaded automatically, the Atari's floppy drive was read for additional components during the boot process.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] There was a timeout delay that provided time to manually insert a floppy as the system searched for the extra components.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This could be avoided by inserting a blank disk.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The IBM Personal Computer included ROM-based firmware called the BIOS; one of the functions of that firmware was to perform a power-on self test when the machine was powered up, and then to read software from a boot device and execute it.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Firmware compatible with the BIOS on the IBM Personal Computer is used in IBM PC compatible computers.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The UEFI was developed by Intel, originally for Itanium-based machines, and later also used as an alternative to the BIOS in x86-based machines, including Apple Macs using Intel processors.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Unix workstations originally had vendor-specific ROM-based firmware.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Sun Microsystems later developed OpenBoot, later known as Open Firmware, which incorporated a Forth interpreter, with much of the firmware being written in Forth.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] It was standardized by the IEEE as IEEE standard 1275-1994; firmware that implements that standard was used in PowerPC-based Macs and some other PowerPC-based machines, as well as Sun's own SPARC-based computers.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The Advanced RISC Computing specification defined another firmware standard, which was implemented on some MIPS-based and Alpha-based machines and the SGI Visual Workstation x86-based workstations.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] When a computer is turned off, its software‍—‌including operating systems, application code, and data‍—‌remains stored on non-volatile memory.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] When the computer is powered on, it typically does not have an operating system or its loader in random-access memory (RAM).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The small program that starts this sequence is known as a *bootstrap loader*, *bootstrap* or *boot loader*.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Often, multiple-stage boot loaders are used, during which several programs of increasing complexity load one after the other in a process of chain loading.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Some earlier computer systems, upon receiving a boot signal from a human operator or a peripheral device, may load a very small number of fixed instructions into memory at a specific location, initialize at least one CPU, and then point the CPU to the instructions and start their execution.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] These instructions typically start an input operation from some peripheral device (which may be switch-selectable by the operator).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Smaller computers often use less flexible but more automatic boot loader mechanisms to ensure that the computer starts quickly and with a predetermined software configuration.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] In many desktop computers, for example, the bootstrapping process begins with the CPU executing software contained in ROM (for example, the BIOS of an IBM PC) at a predefined address (some CPUs, including the Intel x86 series are designed to execute this software after reset without outside help).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This software contains rudimentary functionality to search for devices eligible to participate in booting, and load a small program from a special section (most commonly the boot sector) of the most promising device, typically starting at a fixed entry point such as the start of the sector.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] On systems with those constraints, the first program loaded into RAM may not be sufficiently large to load the operating system and, instead, must load another, larger program.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The first program loaded into RAM is called a first-stage boot loader, and the program it loads is called a second-stage boot loader.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] On many embedded CPUs, the CPU built-in boot ROM, sometimes called the zero-stage boot loader, can find and load first-stage boot loaders.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Examples of first-stage (hardware initialization stage) boot loaders include BIOS, UEFI, coreboot, Libreboot and Das U-Boot.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] On the IBM PC, the boot loader in the Master Boot Record (MBR) and the Partition Boot Record (PBR) was coded to require at least 32 KB (later expanded to 64 KB) of system memory and only use instructions supported by the original 8088/8086 processors.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The second-stage boot loader does not need drivers for its own operation, but may instead use generic storage access methods provided by system firmware such as the BIOS, UEFI or Open Firmware, though typically with restricted hardware functionality and lower performance.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Many boot loaders (like GNU GRUB, rEFInd, Windows's BOOTMGR, Syslinux, and Windows NT/2000/XP's NTLDR) can be configured to give the user multiple booting choices.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Some boot loaders can also load other boot loaders; for example, GRUB loads BOOTMGR instead of loading Windows directly.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Usually, a default choice is preselected with a time delay during which a user can press a key to change the choice; after this delay, the default choice is automatically run so normal booting can occur without interaction.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The boot process can be considered complete when the computer is ready to interact with the user, or the operating system is capable of running system programs or application programs.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Some boot loaders, such as Das U-Boot and iBoot, include both first- and second-stage boot functions.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Many embedded systems must boot immediately.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] For example, waiting a minute for a digital television or a GPS navigation device to start is generally unacceptable.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Therefore, such devices have software systems in ROM or flash memory so the device can begin functioning immediately; little or no loading is necessary, because the loading can be precomputed and stored on the ROM when the device is made.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Large and complex systems may have boot procedures that proceed in multiple phases until finally the operating system and other programs are loaded and ready to execute.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Because operating systems are designed as if they never start or stop, a boot loader might load the operating system, configure itself as a mere process within that system, and then irrevocably transfer control to the operating system.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The boot loader then terminates normally as any other process would.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Most computers are also capable of booting over a computer network.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] In this scenario, the operating system is stored on the disk of a server, and certain parts of it are transferred to the client using a simple protocol such as the Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] After these parts have been transferred, the operating system takes over control of the booting process.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] As with the second-stage boot loader, network booting begins by using generic network access methods provided by the network interface's boot ROM, which typically contains a Preboot Execution Environment (PXE) image.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] No drivers are required, but the system functionality is limited until the operating system kernel and drivers are transferred and started.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] As a result, once the ROM-based booting has completed it is entirely possible to network boot into an operating system that itself does not have the ability to use the network interface.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The boot device is the storage device from which the operating system is loaded.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Older, less common BIOS-bootable devices include floppy disk drives, Zip drives, and LS-120 drives.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] IBM-compatible PCs are examples that use horizontal integrated hardware and UEFI/BIOS firmware.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Typically, the system firmware (UEFI or BIOS) will allow the user to configure a *boot order*.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] If the boot order is set to "first, the DVD drive; second, the hard disk drive", then the firmware will try to boot from the DVD drive, and if this fails (e.g., because there is no DVD in the drive), it will try to boot from the local hard disk drive.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] For example, on a PC with Windows installed on the hard drive, the user could set the boot order to the one given above, and then insert a Linux Live CD in order to try out Linux without having to install an operating system onto the hard drive.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This is an example of dual booting, in which the user chooses which operating system to start after the computer has performed its power-on self-test (POST).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Several devices are available that enable the user to *quick-boot* into what is usually a variant of Linux for various simple tasks such as Internet access; examples are Splashtop and Latitude ON.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This memory location typically contains a jump instruction that transfers execution to the location of the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) start-up program.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This program runs a power-on self-test (POST) to check and initialize required devices such as main memory (DRAM), the PCI bus and the PCI devices (including running embedded option ROMs).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] One of the most involved steps is setting up DRAM over SPD, further complicated by the fact that, at this point, memory is very limited.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] After initializing required hardware, the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) goes through a pre-configured list of non-volatile storage devices ("boot device sequence") until it finds one that is bootable.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Once the BIOS has found a bootable device it loads the boot sector to linear address 7C00h (usually segment:offset 0000h:7C00h, but some BIOSes erroneously use 07C0h:0000h) and transfers execution to the boot code.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] In the case of a hard disk, this is referred to as the Master Boot Record (MBR).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The conventional MBR code checks the MBR's partition table for a partition set as *bootable* (the one with *active* flag set).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] If an active partition is found, the MBR code loads the boot sector code from that partition, known as Volume Boot Record (VBR), and executes it.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The MBR boot code is often operating-system specific.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The boot sector code is the first-stage boot loader.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The boot loader was then able to load the first three sectors of the file into memory, which happened to contain another embedded boot loader able to load the remainder of the file into memory.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] When Microsoft added LBA and FAT32 support, they even switched to a boot loader reaching over *two* physical sectors and using 386 instructions for size reasons.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] At the same time, other vendors managed to squeeze much more functionality into a single boot sector without relaxing the original constraints on only minimal available memory (32 KB) and processor support (8088/8086).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] For example, DR-DOS boot sectors are able to locate the boot file in the FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32 file system, and load it into memory as a whole via CHS or LBA, even if the file is not stored in a fixed location and in consecutive sectors.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The VBR is often OS-specific; however, its main function is to load and execute the operating system boot loader file (such as `bootmgr` or `ntldr`), which is the second-stage boot loader, from an active partition.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Then the boot loader loads the OS kernel from the storage device.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] If there is no active partition, or the active partition's boot sector is invalid, the MBR may load a secondary boot loader which will select a partition (often via user input) and load its boot sector, which usually loads the corresponding operating system kernel.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] In some cases, the MBR may also attempt to load secondary boot loaders before trying to boot the active partition.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] If all else fails, it should issue an INT 18h BIOS interrupt call (followed by an INT 19h just in case INT 18h would return) in order to give back control to the BIOS, which would then attempt to boot off other devices, attempt a remote boot via network.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Many modern systems (Intel Macs and newer PCs) use UEFI.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Unlike BIOS, UEFI (not **Legacy boot** via CSM) does not rely on boot sectors, UEFI system loads the boot loader (**EFI application** file in USB disk or in the EFI System Partition) directly, and the OS kernel is loaded by the boot loader.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] It is difficult to hardwire all the required logic for handling such devices, so an integrated boot ROM is used instead in such scenarios.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Also, a boot ROM may be able to load a boot loader or diagnostic program via serial interfaces like UART, SPI, USB and so on.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This feature is often used for system recovery purposes, or it could also be used for initial non-volatile memory programming when there is no software available in the non-volatile memory yet.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Many modern microcontrollers (e.g., flash memory controller on USB flash drives) have firmware ROM integrated directly into their silicon.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Some embedded system designs may also include an intermediary boot sequence step.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] For example, Das U-Boot may be split into two stages: the platform would load a small SPL (Secondary Program Loader), which is a stripped-down version of U-Boot, and the SPL would do some initial hardware configuration (e.g.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] DRAM initialization using CPU cache as RAM) and load the larger, fully featured version of U-Boot.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Such embedded systems may used highly customized and vertical integrated hardware and software, and their boot programs may be simpler.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Some CPUs and SoCs may not use CPU cache as RAM on boot process, they use an integrated boot processor to do some hardware configuration to reduce cost.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] It is also possible to take control of a system by using a hardware debug interface such as JTAG.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Such an interface may be used to write the boot loader program into bootable non-volatile memory (e.g. flash) by instructing the processor core to perform the necessary actions to program non-volatile memory.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Alternatively, the debug interface may be used to upload some diagnostic or boot code into RAM, and then to start the processor core and instruct it to execute the uploaded code.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] This allows, for example, the recovery of embedded systems where no software remains on any supported boot device, and where the processor does not have any integrated boot ROM.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] JTAG is a standard and popular interface; many CPUs, microcontrollers and other devices are manufactured with JTAG interfaces (as of 2009).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Some microcontrollers provide special hardware interfaces that cannot be used to take arbitrary control of a system or directly run code, but instead allow the insertion of boot code into bootable non-volatile memory (like flash memory) via simple protocols.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Then, at the manufacturing phase, such interfaces are used to inject boot code (and possibly other code) into non-volatile memory.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] After system reset, the microcontroller begins to execute code programmed into its non-volatile memory, just like usual processors use ROMs for booting.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Most notably, this technique is used by Atmel AVR microcontrollers, and by others as well.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] In many cases, such interfaces are implemented by hardwired logic.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] In other cases, such interfaces could be created by software running in integrated on-chip boot ROM from GPIO pins.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Most DSPs have a serial mode boot and a parallel mode boot, such as the host port interface (HPI boot).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] In the case of DSPs, there is often a second microprocessor or microcontroller present in the system design, and this is responsible for overall system behavior, interrupt handling, dealing with external events, user interface, etc., while the DSP is dedicated to signal processing tasks only.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] In such systems, the DSP could be booted by another processor, which is sometimes referred as the *host processor* (giving name to a Host Port).
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Such a processor is also sometimes referred to as the *master*, since it usually boots first from its own memories and then controls overall system behavior, including booting of the DSP, and then further controls the DSP's behavior.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The DSP often lacks its own boot memories and relies on the host processor to supply the required code instead.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The most notable systems with such a design are cell phones, modems, audio and video players and so on, where a DSP and a CPU/microcontroller coexist.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Many FPGA chips load their configuration from an external configuration ROM, typically a serial EEPROM, on power-up.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Various measures have been implemented that enhance the security of the booting process.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Some of them are made mandatory, others can be disabled or enabled by the end user.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Traditionally, booting did not involve the use of cryptography.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The security can be bypassed by unlocking the boot loader, which might or might not be approved by the manufacturer.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Modern boot loaders make use of concurrency, meaning they can run multiple processor cores and threads at the same time, which adds extra layers of complexity to secure booting.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Matthew Garrett argued that booting security serves a legitimate goal, but in doing so chooses defaults that are hostile to users.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] The system might exhibit its erroneous state in, for example, an explicit bootloop or a blue screen of death, before recovery is indicated.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Detection of an erroneous state may require a distributed event store and stream-processing platform for real-time operation of a distributed system.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] An erroneous state can trigger bootloops; this state can be caused by misconfiguration from previously known-good operations.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Recovery attempts from that erroneous state then enter a reboot, in an attempt to return to a known-good state.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] In Windows OS operations, for example, the recovery procedure was to reboot three times, the reboots needed to return to a usable menu.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] Recovery might be specified via Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML), which can also implement Single sign-on (SSO) for some applications; in the zero trust security model, identification, authorization, and authentication are separable concerns in an SSO session.
[src:secure-boot-measured/booting] When recovery of a site is indicated (viz., a blue screen of death is displayed on an airport terminal screen) personal site visits might be required to remediate the situation.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] In computer security, a **chain of trust** is established by validating each component of hardware and software from the end entity up to the root certificate.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] It is intended to ensure that only trusted software and hardware can be used while still retaining flexibility.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] A chain of trust is designed to allow multiple users to create and use the software on the system, which would be more difficult if all the keys were stored directly in hardware.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] It starts with hardware that will only boot from software that is digitally signed (bootloader).
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] The signing authority will only sign boot programs that enforce security, such as only running programs that are themselves signed, or only allowing signed code to have access to certain features of the machine.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] This process may continue for several layers.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] This process results in a chain of trust.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] The final software can be trusted to have certain properties because if it had been illegally modified its signature would be invalid, and the previous software would not have executed it.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] The previous software can be trusted, because it, in turn, would not have been loaded if its signature had been invalid.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] The trustworthiness of each layer is guaranteed by the one before, back to the trust anchor.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] It would be possible to have the hardware check the suitability (signature) for every single piece of software.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] However, this would not produce the flexibility that a "chain" provides.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] In a chain, any given link can be replaced with a different version to provide different properties, without having to go all the way back to the trust anchor.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] This use of multiple layers is an application of a general technique to improve scalability and is analogous to the use of multiple certificates in a certificate chain.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] In computer security, digital certificates are verified using a chain of trust.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] The trust anchor for the digital certificate is the root certificate authority (CA).
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] The certificate hierarchy is a structure of certificates that allows individuals to verify the validity of a certificate's issuer.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] Certificates are issued and signed by certificates that reside higher in the certificate hierarchy, so the validity and trustworthiness of a given certificate is determined by the corresponding validity of the certificate that signed it.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] The chain of trust of a certificate chain is an ordered list of certificates, containing an end-user subscriber certificate and intermediate certificates (that represents the intermediate CA), that enables the receiver to verify that the sender and all intermediate certificates are trustworthy.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] This process is best described in the page *Intermediate certificate authority*.
[src:secure-boot-measured/chain-of-trust] See also X.509 certificate chains for a description of these concepts in a widely used standard for digital certificates.
[src:secure-boot-measured/root-of-trust] In cryptographic systems with hierarchical structure, a **trust anchor** is an authoritative entity for which trust is assumed and not derived.
[src:secure-boot-measured/root-of-trust] In the X.509 architecture, a root certificate would be the trust anchor from which the whole chain of trust is derived.
[src:secure-boot-measured/root-of-trust] The trust anchor must be in the possession of the trusting party beforehand to make any further certificate path validation possible.
[src:secure-boot-measured/root-of-trust] Most operating systems provide a built-in list of self-signed root certificates to act as trust anchors for applications.
[src:secure-boot-measured/root-of-trust] The Firefox web browser also provides its own list of trust anchors.
[src:secure-boot-measured/root-of-trust] The end-user of an operating system or web browser is implicitly trusting in the correct operation of that software, and the software manufacturer in turn is delegating trust for certain cryptographic operations to the certificate authorities responsible for the root certificates.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Trusted Computing proponents such as International Data Corporation, the Enterprise Strategy Group and Endpoint Technologies Associates state that the technology will make computers safer, less prone to viruses and malware, and thus more reliable from an end-user perspective.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] They also state that Trusted Computing will allow computers and servers to offer improved computer security over that which is currently available.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Opponents often state that this technology will be used primarily to enforce digital rights management policies (imposed restrictions to the owner) and not to increase computer security.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Chip manufacturers Intel and AMD, hardware manufacturers such as HP and Dell, and operating system providers such as Microsoft include Trusted Computing in their products if enabled.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Army requires that every new PC it purchases comes with a Trusted Platform Module (TPM).
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] As of July 3, 2007, so does virtually the entire United States Department of Defense.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The endorsement key is a 2048-bit RSA public and private key pair that is created randomly on the chip at manufacture time and cannot be changed.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The private key never leaves the chip, while the public key is used for attestation and for encryption of sensitive data sent to the chip, as occurs during the TPM_TakeOwnership command.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The TPM should be designed to make the extraction of this key by hardware analysis hard, but tamper resistance is not a strong requirement.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Memory curtaining extends common memory protection techniques to provide full isolation of sensitive areas of memory—for example, locations containing cryptographic keys.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Even the operating system does not have full access to curtained memory.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The exact implementation details are vendor specific.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Sealed storage protects private information by binding it to platform configuration information including the software and hardware being used.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] This means the data can be released only to a particular combination of software and hardware.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Sealed storage can be used for DRM enforcing.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] For example, users who keep a song on their computer that has not been licensed to be listened will not be able to play it.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Currently, a user can locate the song, listen to it, and send it to someone else, play it in the software of their choice, or back it up (and in some cases, use circumvention software to decrypt it).
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Alternatively, the user may use software to modify the operating system's DRM routines to have it leak the song data once, say, a temporary license was acquired.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Using sealed storage, the song is securely encrypted using a key bound to the trusted platform module so that only the unmodified and untampered music player on his or her computer can play it.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] In this DRM architecture, this might also prevent people from listening to the song after buying a new computer, or upgrading parts of their current one, except after explicit permission of the vendor of the song.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Remote attestation allows changes to the user's computer to be detected by authorized parties.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] For example, software companies can identify unauthorized changes to software, including users modifying their software to circumvent commercial digital rights restrictions.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] It works by having the hardware generate a certificate stating what software is currently running.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The computer can then present this certificate to a remote party to show that unaltered software is currently executing.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Numerous remote attestation schemes have been proposed for various computer architectures, including Intel, RISC-V, and ARM.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Remote attestation is usually combined with public-key encryption so that the information sent can only be read by the programs that requested the attestation, and not by an eavesdropper.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] To take the song example again, the user's music player software could send the song to other machines, but only if they could attest that they were running an authorized copy of the music player software.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] To preserve the privacy of attestation responders, Direct Anonymous Attestation has been proposed as a solution, which uses a group signature scheme to prevent revealing the identity of individual signers.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Proof of space (PoS) have been proposed to be used for malware detection, by determining whether the L1 cache of a processor is empty (e.g., has enough space to evaluate the PoSpace routine without cache misses) or contains a routine that resisted being evicted.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The Microsoft products Windows Vista, Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows RT make use of a Trusted Platform Module to facilitate BitLocker Drive Encryption.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Other known applications with runtime encryption and the use of secure enclaves include the Signal messenger and the e-prescription service ("E-Rezept") by the German government.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Trusted Computing would allow companies to create a digital rights management (DRM) system which would be very hard to circumvent, though not impossible.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Sealed storage could be used to prevent the user from opening the file with an unauthorized player or computer.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Remote attestation could be used to authorize play only by music players that enforce the record company's rules.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The music would be played from curtained memory, which would prevent the user from making an unrestricted copy of the file while it is playing, and secure I/O would prevent capturing what is being sent to the sound system.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Circumventing such a system would require either manipulation of the computer's hardware, capturing the analogue (and thus degraded) signal using a recording device or a microphone, or breaking the security of the system.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] New business models for use of software (services) over Internet may be boosted by the technology.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] By strengthening the DRM system, one could base a business model on renting programs for a specific time periods or "pay as you go" models.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] For instance, one could download a music file which could only be played a certain number of times before it becomes unusable, or the music file could be used only within a certain time period.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Trusted Computing could be used to combat cheating in online games.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Some players modify their game copy in order to gain unfair advantages in the game; remote attestation, secure I/O and memory curtaining could be used to determine that all players connected to a server were running an unmodified copy of the software.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Trusted Computing could be used to guarantee participants in a grid computing system are returning the results of the computations they claim to be instead of forging them.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] This would allow large scale simulations to be run (say a climate simulation) without expensive redundant computations to guarantee malicious hosts are not undermining the results to achieve the conclusion they want.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The Electronic Frontier Foundation and the Free Software Foundation criticize that trust in the underlying companies is not deserved and that the technology puts too much power and control into the hands of those who design systems and software.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] They also state that it may cause consumers to lose anonymity in their online interactions, as well as mandating technologies Trusted Computing opponents say are unnecessary.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] They suggest Trusted Computing as a possible enabler for future versions of mandatory access control, copy protection, and DRM.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Some security experts, such as Alan Cox and Bruce Schneier, have spoken out against Trusted Computing, believing it will provide computer manufacturers and software authors with increased control to impose restrictions on what users are able to do with their computers.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] There are concerns that Trusted Computing would have an anti-competitive effect on the IT market.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] There is concern amongst critics that it will not always be possible to examine the hardware components on which Trusted Computing relies, the Trusted Platform Module, which is the ultimate hardware system where the core 'root' of trust in the platform has to reside.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] If not implemented correctly, it presents a security risk to overall platform integrity and protected data.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The specifications, as published by the Trusted Computing Group, are open and are available for anyone to review.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] However, the final implementations by commercial vendors will not necessarily be subjected to the same review process.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] In addition, the world of cryptography can often move quickly, and that hardware implementations of algorithms might create an inadvertent obsolescence.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Trusting networked computers to controlling authorities rather than to individuals may create digital imprimaturs.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] One of the early motivations behind trusted computing was a desire by media and software corporations for stricter DRM technology to prevent users from freely sharing and using potentially copyrighted or private files without explicit permission.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] An example could be downloading a music file from a band: the band's record company could come up with rules for how the band's music can be used.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] For example, they might want the user to play the file only three times a day without paying additional money.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Also, they could use remote attestation to only send their music to a music player that enforces their rules: sealed storage would prevent the user from opening the file with another player that did not enforce the restrictions.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Memory curtaining would prevent the user from making an unrestricted copy of the file while it is playing, and secure output would prevent capturing what is sent to the sound system.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] A user who wanted to switch to a competing program might find that it would be impossible for that new program to read old data, as the information would be "locked in" to the old program.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] It could also make it impossible for the user to read or modify their data except as specifically permitted by the software.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The law in many countries allows users certain rights over data whose copyright they do not own (including text, images, and other media), often under headings such as fair use or public interest.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Depending on jurisdiction, these may cover issues such as whistleblowing, production of evidence in court, quoting or other small-scale usage, backups of owned media, and making a copy of owned material for personal use on other owned devices or systems.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The steps implicit in trusted computing have the practical effect of preventing users exercising these legal rights.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] A service that requires external validation or permission - such as a music file or game that requires connection with the vendor to confirm permission to play or use - is vulnerable to that service being withdrawn or no longer updated.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] A number of incidents have already occurred where users, having purchased music or video media, have found their ability to watch or listen to it suddenly stop due to vendor policy or cessation of service, or server inaccessibility, at times with no compensation.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Alternatively in some cases the vendor refuses to provide services in future which leaves purchased material only usable on the present -and increasingly obsolete- hardware (so long as it lasts) but not on any hardware that may be purchased in future.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Some opponents of Trusted Computing advocate "owner override": allowing an owner who is confirmed to be physically present to allow the computer to bypass restrictions and use the secure I/O path.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Such an override would allow remote attestation to a user's specification, e.g., to create certificates that say Internet Explorer is running, even if a different browser is used.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Instead of preventing software change, remote attestation would indicate when the software has been changed without owner's permission.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Trusted Computing Group members have refused to implement owner override.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Proponents of trusted computing believe that owner override defeats the trust in other computers since remote attestation can be forged by the owner.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Owner override offers the security and enforcement benefits to a machine owner, but does not allow them to trust other computers, because their owners could waive rules or restrictions on their own computers.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Under this scenario, once data is sent to someone else's computer, whether it be a diary, a DRM music file, or a joint project, that other person controls what security, if any, their computer will enforce on their copy of those data.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] This has the potential to undermine the applications of trusted computing to enforce DRM, control cheating in online games and attest to remote computations for grid computing.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Because a Trusted Computing equipped computer is able to uniquely attest to its own identity, it will be possible for vendors and others who possess the ability to use the attestation feature to zero in on the identity of the user of TC-enabled software with a high degree of certainty.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Such a capability is contingent on the reasonable chance that the user at some time provides user-identifying information, whether voluntarily, indirectly, or simply through inference of many seemingly benign pieces of data.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] (e.g. search records, as shown through simple study of the AOL search records leak).
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] One common way that information can be obtained and linked is when a user registers a computer just after purchase.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Another common way is when a user provides identifying information to the website of an affiliate of the vendor.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] While proponents of TC point out that online purchases and credit transactions could potentially be more secure as a result of the remote attestation capability, this may cause the computer user to lose expectations of anonymity when using the Internet.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Critics point out that this could have a chilling effect on political free speech, the ability of journalists to use anonymous sources, whistle blowing, political blogging and other areas where the public needs protection from retaliation through anonymity.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The TPM specification offers features and suggested implementations that are meant to address the anonymity requirement.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] By using a third-party Privacy Certification Authority (PCA), the information that identifies the computer could be held by a trusted third party.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Additionally, the use of direct anonymous attestation (DAA), introduced in TPM v1.2, allows a client to perform attestation while not revealing any personally identifiable or machine information.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The kind of data that must be supplied to the TTP in order to get the trusted status is at present not entirely clear, but the TCG itself admits that "attestation is an important TPM function with significant privacy implications".
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] It is, however, clear that both static and dynamic information about the user computer may be supplied (Ekpubkey) to the TTP (v1.1b), it is not clear what data will be supplied to the “verifier” under v1.2.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The static information will uniquely identify the endorser of the platform, model, details of the TPM, and that the platform (PC) complies with the TCG specifications .
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The dynamic information is described as software running on the computer.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] If a program like Windows is registered in the user's name this in turn will uniquely identify the user.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Another dimension of privacy infringing capabilities might also be introduced with this new technology; how often you use your programs might be possible information provided to the TTP.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] In an exceptional, however practical situation, where a user purchases a pornographic movie on the Internet, the purchaser nowadays, must accept the fact that he has to provide credit card details to the provider, thereby possibly risking being identified.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] With the new technology a purchaser might also risk someone finding out that he (or she) has watched this pornographic movie 1000 times.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] This adds a new dimension to the possible privacy infringement.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The extent of data that will be supplied to the TTP/Verifiers is at present not exactly known, only when the technology is implemented and used will we be able to assess the exact nature and volume of the data that is transmitted.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Trusted Computing requests that all software and hardware vendors will follow the technical specifications released by the Trusted Computing Group in order to allow interoperability between different trusted software stacks.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] However, since at least mid-2006, there have been interoperability problems between the TrouSerS trusted software stack (released as open source software by IBM) and Hewlett-Packard's stack.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Another problem is that the technical specifications are still changing, so it is unclear which is the standard implementation of the trusted stack.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] People have voiced concerns that trusted computing could be used to keep or discourage users from running software created by companies outside of a small industry group.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The concerns about trusted computing being used to shut out competition exist within a broader framework of consumers being concerned about using bundling of products to obscure prices of products and to engage in anti-competitive practices.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Trusted Computing is seen as harmful or problematic to independent and open source software developers.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] In the widely used public-key cryptography, creation of keys can be done on the local computer and the creator has complete control over who has access to it, and consequentially their own security policies.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] In some proposed encryption-decryption chips, a private/public key is permanently embedded into the hardware when it is manufactured, and hardware manufacturers would have the opportunity to record the key without leaving evidence of doing so.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] With this key it would be possible to have access to data encrypted with it, and to authenticate as it.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] It is trivial for a manufacturer to give a copy of this key to the government or the software manufacturers, as the platform must go through steps so that it works with authenticated software.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] A security breach breaking that chain of trust happened to a SIM card manufacturer Gemalto, which in 2010 was infiltrated by US and British spies, resulting in compromised security of cellphone calls.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] It is also critical that one be able to trust that the hardware manufacturers and software developers properly implement trusted computing standards.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Incorrect implementation could be hidden from users, and thus could undermine the integrity of the whole system without users being aware of the flaw.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Since 2004, most major manufacturers have shipped systems that have included Trusted Platform Modules, with associated BIOS support.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] In accordance with the TCG specifications, the user must enable the Trusted Platform Module before it can be used.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Processor manufacturers have included secure enclaves in their design such as ARM TrustZone, Intel Management Engine with SGX and AMD PSP with Secure Encrypted Virtualization.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The Linux kernel has included trusted computing support since version 2.6.13, and there are several projects to implement trusted computing for Linux.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] In January 2005, members of Gentoo Linux's "crypto herd" announced their intention of providing support for TC—in particular support for the Trusted Platform Module.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] There is also a TCG-compliant software stack for Linux named TrouSerS, released under an open source license.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] There are several open-source projects that facilitate the use of confidential computing technology, including EGo, EdgelessDB and MarbleRun from Edgeless Systems, as well as Enarx, which originates from security research at Red Hat.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Some limited form of trusted computing can be implemented on current versions of Microsoft Windows with third-party software.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Major cloud providers such as Microsoft Azure, AWS and Google Cloud Platform have virtual machines with trusted computing features available.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] The Intel Classmate PC (a competitor to the One Laptop Per Child) includes a Trusted Platform Module.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] PrivateCore vCage software can be used to attest x86 servers with TPM chips.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Google enforces Play Integrity API to Android devices with their bootloader unlocked.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Mobile T6 secure operating system simulates the TPM functionality in mobile devices using the ARM TrustZone technology.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-computing] Samsung smartphones come equipped with Samsung Knox that depend on features like Secure Boot, TIMA, MDM, TrustZone and SE Linux.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] A **Trusted Platform Module** (**TPM**) is a secure cryptoprocessor that implements the **ISO/IEC 11889** standard.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Common uses are verifying that the boot process starts from a trusted combination of hardware and software and storing disk encryption keys.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] A TPM 2.0 implementation is part of the Windows 11 system requirements.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The first TPM version that was deployed was 1.1b in 2003.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Trusted Platform Module (TPM) was conceived by a computer industry consortium called Trusted Computing Group (TCG).
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] It evolved into *TPM Main Specification Version 1.2* which was standardized by International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in 2009 as ISO/IEC 11889:2009.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] *TPM Main Specification Version 1.2* was finalized on 3 March 2011 completing its revision.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] On April 9, 2014, the Trusted Computing Group announced a major upgrade to their specification entitled *TPM Library Specification 2.0*.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The group continues work on the standard incorporating errata, algorithmic additions and new commands, with its most recent edition published as 2.0 in November 2019.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] When a new revision is released, it is divided into multiple parts by the Trusted Computing Group.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Each part consists of a document that makes up the whole of the new TPM specification.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] While TPM 2.0 addresses many of the same use cases and has similar features, the details are different.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] TPM 2.0 is not backward compatible with TPM 1.2.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The TPM 2.0 policy authorization includes the 1.2 HMAC, locality, physical presence, and PCR.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] It adds authorization based on an asymmetric digital signature, indirection to another authorization secret, counters and time limits, NVRAM values, a particular command or command parameters, and physical presence.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] It permits the ANDing and ORing of these authorization primitives to construct complex authorization policies.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Computer programs can use a TPM for the authentication of hardware devices, since each TPM chip has a unique and secret Endorsement Key (EK) burned in as it is produced.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Security embedded in hardware provides more protection than a software-only solution.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Its use is restricted in some countries.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The primary scope of TPM is to ensure the integrity of a platform during boot time.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] In this context, "integrity" means "behaves as intended", and a "platform" is any computer device regardless of its operating system.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] This is to ensure that the boot process starts from a trusted combination of hardware and software, and continues until the operating system has fully booted and applications are running.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] When TPM is used, the firmware and the operating system are responsible for ensuring integrity.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] For example, the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) can use TPM to form a root of trust: The TPM contains several Platform Configuration Registers (PCRs) that allow secure storage and reporting of security-relevant metrics.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] These metrics can be used to detect changes to previous configurations and decide how to proceed.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Examples of such use can be found in Linux Unified Key Setup (LUKS), BitLocker and PrivateCore vCage memory encryption.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Another example of platform integrity via TPM is in the use of Microsoft Office 365 licensing and Outlook Exchange.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Another example of TPM use for platform integrity is the Trusted Execution Technology (TXT), which creates a chain of trust.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] It could remotely attest that a computer is using the specified hardware and software.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Full disk encryption utilities, such as dm-crypt, can use this technology to protect the keys used to encrypt the computer's storage devices and provide integrity authentication for a trusted boot pathway that includes firmware and the boot sector.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] In 2006, new laptops began being sold with a built-in TPM chip.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] In the future, this concept could be co-located on an existing motherboard chip in computers, or any other device where the TPM facilities could be employed, such as a cellphone.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] On a PC, either the Low Pin Count (LPC) bus or the Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI) bus is used to connect to the TPM chip.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The official TCG reference implementation of the TPM 2.0 Specification has been developed by Microsoft.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] It is licensed under BSD License and the source code is available on GitHub.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] In 2018, Intel open-sourced its Trusted Platform Module 2.0 (TPM2) software stack with support for Linux and Microsoft Windows.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The source code is hosted on GitHub and licensed under BSD License.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Infineon funded the development of an open source TPM middleware that complies with the Software Stack (TSS) Enhanced System API (ESAPI) specification of the TCG.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] It was developed by Fraunhofer Institute for Secure Information Technology (SIT).
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] IBM's Software TPM 2.0 is an implementation of the TCG TPM 2.0 specification.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] It is based on the TPM specification Parts 3 and 4 and source code donated by Microsoft.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] It contains additional files to complete the implementation.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The source code is hosted on SourceForge and GitHub and licensed under BSD License.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] In 2022, AMD announced that under certain circumstances their fTPM implementation causes performance problems.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] A fix is available in form of a BIOS-Update.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The Trusted Computing Group (TCG) has faced resistance to the deployment of this technology in some areas, where some authors see possible uses not specifically related to Trusted Computing, which may raise privacy concerns.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The concerns include the abuse of remote validation of software to decide what software is allowed to run, and possible ways to follow actions taken by the user and record them in a database in a manner that is completely undetectable to the user.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The TrueCrypt disk encryption utility, as well as its derivative VeraCrypt, do not support TPM.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The original TrueCrypt developers were of the opinion that the exclusive purpose of the TPM is "to protect against attacks that require the attacker to have administrator privileges, or physical access to the computer".
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The attacker who has physical or administrative access to a computer can circumvent TPM, e.g., by installing a hardware keystroke logger, by resetting TPM, or by capturing memory contents and retrieving TPM-issued keys.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The condemning text goes so far as to claim that TPM is entirely redundant.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The VeraCrypt publisher has reproduced the original allegation with no changes other than replacing "TrueCrypt" with "VeraCrypt".
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The author is right that, after achieving either unrestricted physical access or administrative privileges, it is only a matter of time before other security measures in place are bypassed.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] However, stopping an attacker in possession of administrative privileges has never been one of the goals of TPM (see § Uses for details), and TPM can stop some physical tampering.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] In 2015, Richard Stallman suggested replacing the term "trusted computing" with the term "treacherous computing" due to the danger that the computer can be made to systematically disobey its owner if the cryptographical keys are kept secret from them.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] In August 2023, Linus Torvalds, who was frustrated with AMD fTPM's stuttering bugs, opined, "Let's just disable the stupid fTPM `hwrnd` thing." He said the CPU-based random number generation, `rdrand`, was equally suitable, despite having its share of bugs.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] In 2010, Christopher Tarnovsky presented an attack against TPMs at Black Hat Briefings, where he claimed to be able to extract secrets from a single TPM.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] He was able to do this after 6 months of work by inserting a probe and spying on an internal bus for the Infineon SLE 66 CL PC.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] In case of physical access, computers with TPM 1.2 are vulnerable to cold boot attacks as long as the system is on or can be booted without a passphrase from shutdown, sleep or hibernation, which is the default setup for Windows computers with BitLocker full disk encryption.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] A fix was proposed, which has been adopted in the specifications for TPM 2.0.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] In 2009, the concept of shared authorisation data in TPM 1.2 was found to be flawed.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] An adversary given access to the data could spoof responses from the TPM.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] In 2015, as part of the Snowden revelations, it was revealed that in 2010 a US CIA team claimed at an internal conference to have carried out a differential power analysis attack against TPMs that was able to extract secrets.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Main Trusted Boot (tboot) distributions before November 2017 are affected by a dynamic root of trust for measurement (DRTM) attack CVE-2017-16837, which affects computers running on Intel's Trusted eXecution Technology (TXT) for the boot-up routine.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] In October 2017, it was reported that a code library developed by Infineon, which had been in widespread use in its TPMs, contained a vulnerability, known as ROCA, which generated weak RSA key pairs that allowed private keys to be inferred from public keys.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] As a result, all systems depending upon the privacy of such weak keys are vulnerable to compromise, such as identity theft or spoofing.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Cryptosystems that store encryption keys directly in the TPM without blinding could be at particular risk to these types of attacks, as passwords and other factors would be meaningless if the attacks can extract encryption secrets.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Infineon has released firmware updates for its TPMs to manufacturers who have used them.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] In 2018, a design flaw in the TPM 2.0 specification for the static root of trust for measurement (SRTM) was reported (CVE-2018-6622).
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] It allows an adversary to reset and forge platform configuration registers which are designed to securely hold measurements of software that are used for bootstrapping a computer.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Fixing it requires hardware-specific firmware patches.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] An attacker abuses power interrupts and TPM state restores to trick TPM into thinking that it is running on non-tampered components.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] In 2021, the Dolos Group showed an attack on a discrete TPM, where the TPM chip itself had some tamper resistance, but the other endpoints of its communication bus did not.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] They read a full-disk-encryption key as it was transmitted across the motherboard, and used it to decrypt the laptop's SSD.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] As of 2025, a TPM is provided by nearly all PC and notebook manufacturers in their products.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] There are also hybrid types; for example, TPM can be integrated into an Ethernet controller, thus eliminating the need for a separate motherboard component.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Field upgrade is the TCG term for updating the TPM firmware.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The update can be between TPM 1.2 and TPM 2.0, or between firmware versions.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Some vendors limit the number of transitions between 1.2 and 2.0, and some restrict rollback to previous versions.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Platform OEMs such as HP supply an upgrade tool.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Since July 28, 2016, all new Microsoft device models, lines, or series (or updating the hardware configuration of an existing model, line, or series with a major update, such as CPU, graphic cards) implement, and enable by default TPM 2.0.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] TPM endorsement keys (EKs) are asymmetric key pairs unique to each TPM.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The TPM manufacturer usually provisions endorsement key certificates in TPM non-volatile memory.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The certificates assert that the TPM is authentic.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Starting with TPM 2.0, the certificates are in X.509 DER format.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] After the TPM was manufactured, the EKs cannot be changed.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] For fTPM, the EKs are stored on CPU / chipset when it was manufactured.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] These manufacturers typically provide their certificate authority root (and sometimes intermediate) certificates on their web sites.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] To utilize a TPM, the user needs a software library that communicates with the TPM and provides a friendlier API than the raw TPM communication.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Currently, there are several such open-source TPM 2.0 libraries.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Some of them also support TPM 1.2, but mostly TPM 1.2 chips are now deprecated and modern development is focused on TPM 2.0.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Typically, a TPM library provides an API with one-to-one mappings to TPM commands.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The TCG specification calls this layer the System API (SAPI).
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] This way, the user has more control over the TPM operations, but the complexity is high.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] To hide some of the complexity, most libraries also offer simpler ways to invoke complex TPM operations.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] The TCG specification call these two layers Enhanced System API (ESAPI) and Feature API (FAPI).
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] There is currently only one stack that follows the TCG specification.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] All the other available open-source TPM libraries use their own form of richer API.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] There is an application note about an example project for the AURIX 32-bit SoC using the tpm2-tss library.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] Requires additional libraries (dotnet) to run on Linux.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] These TPM libraries are sometimes also called TPM stacks, because they provide the interface for the developer or user to interact with the TPM.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] As seen from the table, the TPM stacks abstract the operating system and transport layer, so the user could migrate one application between platforms.
[src:secure-boot-measured/trusted-platform-module] For example, by using TPM stack API the user would interact the same way with a TPM, regardless if the physical chip is connected over SPI, I2C or LPC interface to the Host system.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI replaces the BIOS that was present in the boot ROM of all personal computers that are IBM PC compatible, although it can provide backwards compatibility with the BIOS using CSM booting.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Unlike the BIOS, which was originally developed by IBM as a proprietary architecture, the UEFI specification is managed by an industry consortium.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Most production firmware implementations for both remain proprietary.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Intel developed the original *Extensible Firmware Interface* (*EFI*) specification.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The last Intel version of EFI was 1.10 released in 2005.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Subsequent versions have been developed as UEFI by the UEFI Forum.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI is independent of platform and programming language, but C is used for the reference implementation TianoCore EDKII.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The original motivation for EFI came during early development of the first Intel–HP Itanium systems in the mid-1990s.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] BIOS limitations had become too restrictive for the larger server platforms for which Itanium was targeted.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The effort to address these concerns began in 1998 and was initially called *Intel Boot Initiative*.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It was later renamed to *Extensible Firmware Interface* (EFI).
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The first open-source UEFI implementation, Tiano, was released by Intel in 2004.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Tiano has since then been superseded by EDK and EDK II and is now maintained by the TianoCore community.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In July 2008, Intel ceased its development of the EFI specification at version 1.10 and contributed it to the Unified EFI Forum, which has developed the specification as the *Unified Extensible Firmware Interface* (UEFI).
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The original EFI specification remains owned by Intel, which exclusively provides licenses for EFI-based products, but the UEFI specification is owned by the UEFI Forum.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Version 2.0 of the UEFI specification was released on 31 January 2006.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Version 2.1 of the UEFI specification was released on 7 January 2007.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It added network authentication and the user interface architecture ("Human Interface Infrastructure" in UEFI).
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Version 2.3.1 of the UEFI specification was released on 6 April 2011.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It added Secure Boot, as well as ARM architecture support.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In October 2018, Arm introduced Arm ServerReady, a compliance certification program intended to ensure standard operating systems and hypervisors run on Arm-based servers.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The program requires the system firmware to comply with Server Base Boot Requirements (SBBR).
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] SBBR requires UEFI, ACPI and SMBIOS compliance.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In October 2020, Arm announced the extension of the program to the edge and IoT market.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The new program name is Arm SystemReady.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Many Linux and BSD distributions can support both recipes.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In December 2018, Microsoft announced Project Mu, a fork of TianoCore EDK II used in Microsoft Surface and Hyper-V products.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The project incorporates a service-based firmware delivery model.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The latest UEFI specification, version 2.11, was published in December 2024.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI supports processor architectures that are 32-bit or higher.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, only processors with a little-endian mode are supported.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Unofficial UEFI support is under development for POWERPC64 by implementing TianoCore EDK II on top of OPAL, the OpenPOWER abstraction layer, running in little-endian mode.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For MIPS, there also exists an unofficial project, based on the original EDK.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, both projects have since been abandoned as of November 2016 and September 2015 respectively.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI only allows executing UEFI applications that match the firmware's bit-width, even if the processor supports smaller or larger bit-widths.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For example, a 64-bit UEFI firmware may only execute 64-bit UEFI applications, even if the processor has a 32-bit processor mode.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Some low-end computers have been shipped with 32-bit UEFI firmware running on 64-bit CPUs.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Once a UEFI application ends the boot services and gets granted full control over the system, it becomes possible to change the processor execution mode.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, calling runtime services requires shortly changing back to the original processor mode, as runtime services may only be called from the same processor mode as the firmware implementation.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The Linux kernel added support for booting 64-bit kernels on 32-bit UEFI firmware implementations with x86-64 CPUs since version 3.15, requiring the UEFI boot loader to support the EFI handover protocol.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The EFI handover protocol allows UEFI boot loaders to defer the UEFI initialization to the kernel's EFI boot stub, so that only the kernel does the UEFI initialization.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In addition to the standard PC disk partition scheme that uses a master boot record (MBR), UEFI also works with the GUID Partition Table (GPT) partitioning scheme, which is free from many of the limitations of MBR.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In particular, the MBR limits on the number and size of disk partitions (up to four primary partitions per disk, and up to 2 TB (2 × 240 bytes) per disk) are relaxed.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] More specifically, GPT allows for a maximum disk and partition size of 8 ZiB (8 × 270 bytes) with 512 byte sectors.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The UEFI specification only supports FAT12/16/32 partitions that are on GPT or MBR disks as well as El Torito-formatted optical discs.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Although GPT is a part of the UEFI standard, it may also be usable by BIOS PCs to boot an operating system off of.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Support for GPT in Linux is enabled by turning on the option `CONFIG_EFI_PARTITION` (EFI GUID Partition Support) during kernel configuration.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This option allows Linux to recognize and use GPT disks after the system firmware passes control over the system to Linux.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For reverse compatibility, Linux can use GPT disks in BIOS-based systems for both data storage and booting, as both GRUB 2 and Linux are GPT-aware.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Such a setup is usually referred to as *BIOS-GPT*.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] As GPT incorporates the protective MBR, a BIOS-based computer can boot from a GPT disk using a GPT-aware boot loader stored in the protective MBR's bootstrap code area.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In the case of GRUB, such a configuration requires a BIOS boot partition for GRUB to embed its second-stage code due to absence of the post-MBR gap in GPT partitioned disks (which is taken over by the GPT's *Primary Header* and *Primary Partition Table*).
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Commonly 1 MB in size, this partition's Globally Unique Identifier (GUID) in GPT scheme is 21686148-6449-6E6F-744E-656564454649 and is used by GRUB only in BIOS-GPT setups.
[src:secure-boot-measured/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] From GRUB's perspective, no such partition type exists in case of MBR partitioning.
